Marcel, Normand, Alcide, Amie, Anselme, Cecile, Clemence, Dominique, Georges.","French:","soldier's name from <i>franc coeur</i> ‘sincere heart’."]},{"name":"Hartin","meanings":["Irish (Donegal): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArtáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Artán</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>Art</i>, a byname meaning ‘bear’ or ‘hero’. Compare   Hart   8.","English: habitational name from Harting (Sussex), from the Old English personal name <i>Heort</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>."]},{"name":"Hartel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Erna, Gunter, Kurt, Lutz, Otto.","German (also <b>Härtel</b>): from a pet form of an ancient Germanic compound personal name based on the element <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’.","French (Normandy): occupational name, a derivative of   Hart   7."]},{"name":"De Hart","meanings":["Dutch: from Middle Dutch <i>hart</i>, modern Dutch <i>hert</i> ‘deer, hart’ or <i>hart</i> ‘heart’ (see   Hart   5), with the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’."]},{"name":"Hardt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Ernst, Erwin, Frieda, Gerhard, Gottlieb, Gunther, Hans, Heinz, Reinhold, Udo.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by woods used as pasture, from Middle High German <i>hart</i>.","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic compound personal name beginning with <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’."]},{"name":"Harten","meanings":["North German: patronymic from   Hart   1.","Dutch: patronymic from   Hart   4.","Dutch (<b>Van Harten</b>): habitational name from a place so named near Renkum, Gelderland."]},{"name":"Hartt","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Hart  ."]},{"name":"Harte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Sinead.","English and North German: variant of   Hart   1.","Dutch: variant of   Hart   4."]},{"name":"Hartjes","meanings":["Dutch: patronymic from a pet form of   Hart   4."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which de